For this, BPDU guard being enabled on a port that connected to a neighbor switch was it. BPDU guard should NOT be enabled on a port that connects to another switch, but on downlink ports that host connect to.

After confirming in 10 mins time that the function of "Errdisable Recovery" worked properly, I did exactly what I would do in a production environment when seeing this: Investigate the error and find the root cause.

Since i enabled "Errdisable recovery" for all causes, depending on the timer interval (for this lab, i kept it at the default 300 seconds<5 mins>) will auto-magically enable the port for the errdisable reasons that were detected.
After enabling "BPDU guard" on SW5, after a few seconds, the switch recieved a BPDU from SW13 and the state of the port met the condition of err-disabled.
The other UDLD mode "normal" would mark the port and inform you that there is an error, but would not disable the port nor stop a potential loop. Which i choose to go with the first mentioned

I set UDLD to 'Aggressive mode' on both sides. What does that mean? This means if the link loses connectivity, and the switch doesnt respond after the switch sends a UDLD frame once a second for 8 seconds, the interface will be put in err-disable mode.

UDLD is a keepalive mechanism. Hellos are sent on a link, if they are rcvd by both sides of the link, everything is good. If the hello messages aren't rcvd, the switch will block the interface. (typically used with fiber links to prevent a loop if one of the fiber cable breaks)
BPDU guard blocks a port from receiving BPDUs of any kind processed on the port on the switch.
So in my lab, i enabled "BPDU guard" on SW5 port Gi1/2, and UDLD (aggressive mode) is enabled on All ports within my topology.

There are alot of causes of Errdisable, tonight i am testing:

1. UDLD
2. BPDU Guard Violation

The goal is to confirm that the expected behavior of Errdisable happens and it "recovers" auto-magically like CS would say.
SOURCE: https://t.co/2Gz28d8zV2

"In other words, the port is automatically disabled by the switch operating system software because of an error condition that is encountered on the port.
When a port is error disabled, it is effectively shut down and no traffic is sent or received on that port."
"If the configuration shows a port to be enabled, but software on the switch detects an error situation on the port, the software shuts down that port."
So the function of Errdisable is this:

So now, that i recreated the enviornment but not the issue, what do I do now?

Share my findings with FortiTAC, and work with them first (only because i trust a switch is going to perform Layer 2 functions better than a Layer 3 device that multifacted)

The other side of that bundle (as long as it's configured in LACP mode 'Active' or 'Passive') is going to accept the LACP PDU that initiated the negotiation to create a bundle and now become a LAG 

(As long as the configuration meets the LAG criteria on both sides)

What does the mode "Active" mean in LACP for a LAG (Or Link Aggreation <i probably spelled it wrong, so what> or just a etherchannel for my cisco folks)

"Active" means that those LACP PDU (packet data units) sent will have a message saying 

"Yo, i wanna become a bundle w/ you"

So i said, let's dig into LAG (or etherchannels for my cisco folks)

So I confirmed that both sides had the correct 'physical' ports, speed and duplex matched, and since they were using the dynamic protocol 'LACP' to create the bundle, i made sure at least 1 side was set 2 active

Rebooted it, and guess what? LAG came up without intervention from me. 

Because here was the issue during the MW. The LAG has to be manually enabled. https://t.co/hT1tr6YLh3

For my case, i only wanted to recreate a LAG being established and being in a 'working' state, then rebooting the Fortigate firewall to see if i see the error that i seen during the Maintinance Window (MW for short)

What does that mean? 

1. Identify what layer your problem exist
2. Bottom up, to some pre-checks to see if everything is working (i.e. L1 - are links up and not disabled on both sides? is it physically connected? Any cable errors?)
3. Then once you reach the layer, start 2 dig

So just imagine if a link kept going up and down in your network, i'm certain (which i've seen) are going to experience intermittment connectivity issues and your switch is going to be working hard processing the traffic.
If a host hasn't communicated in a while, the switch will generate a "unknown unicast broadcast" to find the destination of where the traffic needs to be sent to.

Once non-root switches recieve a TCN with a Topo change flag set, it will set it's MAC address table timer to the same time as the forwarding delay (STP states 'Listening' and 'Learning' which is 30 secs) and flush the entire table.

After bringing down the link, a TCN was generated and sent to SW14, which pushed it to the root SW13. Then SW13 shot out a TCN config BPDU with the topo change flag set. What does this have to do with the MAC address table?
I also tested the behavior of when a neighboring switch which is connected to another switch (SW5 -->SW13) and it's port is in a 'forwarding' state, what would happend?

Errdisabled responded and kept trying to bring the interface back up every 5 mins(300 seconds). To fix, i removed the link (since the CPU was high and terminal was locked) and removed the statically configured MAC address.
I set the MAC address of "TEST-PC" statically into a different VLAN manually. I couldn't capture the error but this produced a "MAC Flap" syslog message from the MATM

After connecting it to SW5, i forced the PC to send a broadcast so SW13 can learn about it (forced a DHCP discover in attempt to get an IP address). SW13 learned about "TEST-PC". Worked normally as it was supposed.

So i decided to break it,
I brought in "TEST-PC" to test the behavior of letting "SW13" learn about it dynamically vs it being statically added by me.
in laymens terms, they can begin adding mac addresses to its table based on the source address of frames recieved on a port.
In my project, I wanted to confirm i know how to view the MAC address table. As long as the switchport is either in a 'Learning' or 'Forwarding' state, the switch can "modify" the MAC address table:
A fundamental concept within my journey up to this point.

In this morning's CCIE studies, I have started phase 3 of my i am "testing operation, functionality and failure" within all topics of the "Switches campus" section. Starting with "Managing the MAC Address table"

This was a fun lab. This completed Phase 2. Now i will move onto Phase 3: Testing failure.
PVST Simulation traffic from the MSTP region SW13 is apart from each vlan is being sent to the Access switch. Along with some other management switch traffic.
I performed a packet capture on the Core link to the Distro in building and from the Core to a Access layer Switch. I wanted to confirm the traffic traversing the link. As you can see,

RootGuard being set on SW13 say this: if i recieve a BPDU from a switch that is superior than me, shut down the port i recieved it on, because i am the root for a reason, so until that's figured out, that's gonna be in a err-disabled state.
bringing the affected interfaces up "auto-magically" --> in the words of Mace Windu aka CS

Which will cause a major catastrophe in my Layer 2 topology and traffic flow. With me having MSTP configured and SW13 being in that MSTP region, links will be disabled every 5 mins due to 'RootGuard' being activated and "errdisable recovery mode"

I also enabled 'bpduguard' on those same links. Here's why, let's say my end users brings in a old switch from their house to give themselves "more ports" at their desk. If it's a older switch, it is probably going to have a lower mac than my current root (SW13)

I enabled 'portfast' on all downlink ports on my access layer switch so that whenever there is a interface state change, there will not be a TCN generated to cause any STP calculations and a flush of the MAC address table on host that have not communicated just barely under 300s
I also wanted to implement some features to make sure my redundant topology was resilient without errors from end users or fellow techs.

Etherchannel misconfiguraton guard helps prevent the misconfig of e-channels. Interfaces in a bundle need to have matching configurations (speed, duplex, trunking on one side, not on the other, etc). I didn't have to configure this because it is enabled by default has a guardrail

I wanted to use LLDP instead of CDP due to LLDP being able to provide more information on neighbor devices and being vendor neutral (in case my client may have some other devices like Fortigate, Aruba switch, etc)

From the previous post, i completed the implementation of my "Switched Campus" deployment by introducing the following:
L2 protocols: LLDP
Etherchannel: Etherchannel Misconfiguration Guard
Spanning Tree Protocol: Portfast, BPDUGuard, LoopGuard and RootGuard

In this morning's CCIE studies, I focused on completing phase 2 of the "Switched Campus" final review project.

Last but not least, I have redundant links to the ISP; each link to the ISP are in vlan 11. For my SVI configured for vlan 11, i set a double quad zero to the GW for the "Switched Campus"
The Core MSTP Region will serve as the Root (SW13 - primary, SW14 -secondary.)

For Spanning Tree, the Core and Distribution are running MSTP. In a production real life environment, i would've implemented a virtual-chassis solution and ran RPVST+. for the sake of the lab, the access switches will be the only switches running RPVST+
For Redundancy and Resiliency, I have FHRP, redundant links and primary and 2 floating static routes to pass traffic from Building 2 to Building 1.
Between the Core and Distro switches, Etherchannels were created. They carry a limited amount of VLANs. Typically those VLANs who have SVIs that will be routing traffic.

Here are the list of VLANs
CORP - 10
ISP - 11
FHRP - 12
WIFI - 20
GUEST - 30
QUARENTINE - 40
SERVERS - 50
NATIVE - 60
MGMT - 99
For security purposes, VLAN 60, has been set as the "native" vlan for all trunks in the topology.
What this also does, is limit the size of the broadcast domain of each VLAN. This protects endpoints from having to process broadcasts sent from users on the same VLAN at Building 1
To further explain how i "ended Layer 2" at Building 2, i pruned all VLANs on the uplinks to Building 1 Core switch except 1,12, and 99
I confirmed that they can handle the amount of devices users at that site will have

In Building 2, I am running a three-tier design. Reason being that the building will encompass 6 times of the users at building 1. Each user will have 3 devices. So i decided to end Layer 2 at the Distro switches SW15 and SW16.
After the network design questionnaire from the customer, the amount of devices all users will have will be well below the MAC address limit and ARP table limit.
As explained in my previous post, I am running a two-tier design at Building 1. Reason being that the Data Center lives in the same building as each stack switch on each floor.

Phase 2 of this project encompassed the following:
VLAN Technologies
Etherchannel
Spanning Tree Protocol
The goal is implement all of the objectives covered in the "Switched Campus" section of the CCIE Practical Exam topics

As of now, only 1/3 have been completed in this lab. I have given myself a timer of 1 hr for each session.

No other vlan has been configured just yet. The goal is to stand up L1 and L2 as much as possible in Phase 1. This means:

1. Physical links between switches are up
2. STP is communicating properly between the MSTP domains and RSTP domains
3. LLDP has been replaced by CDP

In my previous post about my project, the scope of Phase 1 is to stand up all switches within Building 1, Building 2 and the Data Center Core. I left off on configuring the Distribution Layer Switches in Building 1 (SW13 and SW14) with MSTP and Trunks towards the core.

Here is an example of a the 'not' operator returning False because if the value is true, the 'not' operator tells the Boolean to ignore any comparisons that are true
print(not 2 == 2)

The last operator "NOT" was tricky to me, but once i tried it in my interpreter, it made sense.
NOT - The "not" operator will simply negate the expression "true" value
OR - The Boolean "or" operator returns 'True' if any operand is 'True'. It will return 'False' only if both expressions evaluate to 'False'
AND - The Boolean "and" operator returns 'True' if both expressions are 'True. If any expression is 'False' the entire expression is evaluated to 'False'
These have Boolean rules as well:

integers

Sequences (like strings, lists, tuples)
Dictionaries and Sets
Custom classes
"True" is interpreted by python as the number 1, and "False" is interpreted as the number 0.

@CiscoPress But per the #CiscoDevNet OCG, most Software development teams create separate workspaces (or Branches) to maybe add new lines of code before adding it to the code hosted in the default "branch"
@CiscoPress A Branch, is a development workspace for my "project". Normally i am connected to the default workspace which hosts the file.
@CiscoPress With "commit" messages, hashes created when a 'commit' is made to a "branch" and scanning the script to do a difference of the previous version.

@CiscoPress Github host the python scripts i am creating. If i make any changes and 'push' these changes to my remote repository, the remote repository (in this case, Github) will track these changes:

@CiscoPress Now with git, you can just have a local repository, but i am learning that most software development teams have a remote repository to save their work and be their SVC (Software version control) system. Github is the one i am using
@CiscoPress Think of this as your local repository (where your changes are saved, finalized and implemented)

@CiscoPress Think of your Working Directory as your workbench --> you are getting all the parts you bought put together

To fix, i removed the configs from SW2, and STP reconverged properly and PC4 was able to receive an IP address.

If any of the mechanisms weren't in place, for sure, a loop would've "had a field day"

SW1 who is the root and DHCP server is blocking the port towards SW2, and SW3 is blocking on the port towards SW2 due to UDLD shutting down the port and SW1 shutting down the port towards SW3 intermittently since it is recieving superior bpdus from SW3 about SW2

I created a MACL (since this is emulation environment using "copper" cables) to disable SW2 from receiving BPDUs from the STP multicast address and set SW2 as the root.

Now, PC4, needs to get an IP address while all of this is happening. --> but it can't

Why? because it's alot of admin overhead to see the error and manually bring back up a port.

To test this, i broke the lab.

I also implemented "errdisable recovery" for the mechanisms implemented early. What will that do? If any of the switches meet an error condition that will "shut down" a port, the switch will start a time and "auto-magically" in my CS voice, bring the port back up.

Let's assume all the links are "fiber" links, so i enabled UDLD so i won't encounter a loop. What UDLD (aggressive mode) does is that if a link is transmitting bpdus but not recieving bpdus --> it will be assumed that a loop is present and will shut down the port.
Enabling both means that if SW1 recieves a BPDU that is superior from another switch in the topology, it will block that port until it has stopped recieving superior bpdus.

I wanted to put some security mechanisms in place to make sure my end users will continue to reach the internet or other host in the case of L2 errors.

I enabled STP rootguard on SW1 and UDLD on all the switches.

PC4 and PC5 hang off of the non root switches.

SW1 is also serving as the DHCP server

SW1 won the election as the root bridge. SW2 won the election as the designated non-root switch. Which mean SW3 will be blocking one of its ports (in this case Gi0/3 since all the links have the same cost due to the bandwidth being Gigabit port speeds)
Why this topic? --> I think there are enough tutorials of how something is supposed to look in the "working" state, but what about the "broken" state?

The name for this lab is called "STP Havoc"

This lab's choice of music is: "S.T" by The Roots

In today's CCIE studies, i re-explore the behavior of "STP RG", "STP LG" and "UDLD". The goal for this lab is to bring all of the STP topics together and confirm that I know it to the point that it is second nature.

Now, the changes are made to the local repo, but last but not least, i wanted to "push" those same changes to my remote repo (github) to track my journey of learning the python fundamentals! I did that by running the command

"sudo git push (remotename) (branchname)"

Now that it was added to the staging area, and i had no other changes to make, i was in the clear to "commit" my changes to my local repo. by running the command

"sudo git commit -a -m <and a message enclosed by " ">
i didn't specify the file because there is only one file i worked on, so i kept it simple.

Now that i have confirmed i am done making changes to my code, i moved my code to "staging" area where (in my own words) is "ready for shipment if i was a mailman" with the following command:

"sudo git add ."
Doing that, it is now being "untracked" in my working directory by git. I confirmed that by running the command "git status" (as seen in screen shot)

Once i did that, i wanted to create a new file, add some code to it showcasing some basics about variables i watched in Andrei Dumitrescu udemy course "Master Network Automation with Python for Network Engineers" with the following commands:

"sudo touch <name of file>.py"
-Another note, i was in the file directory where the files lived, so there was no need for me to write out the path.

Then, i wanted to remove some files from my local repo, which was performed by running the command:

"sudo git rm <name of file>"

-To note, i have my repo in a protected location that requires elevated privileges, you will see in the screenshot a lot. My method to the madness is to make sure no "rogue" or "bad actors" attempt to do any mischief

I began my initializing the local repository by going to the folder where the repo is located and running the command:

"sudo git init <name of repo (or folder)>"
I kept this lab short, I wanted to go through the process of updating my remote repository locally from my Linux PC.

The goal is to make it second nature.

This was a fun 30 minute lab refreshing me on the election process!

More to come! https://t.co/d8OJw9lUes

As you can see, with that change, now traffic flowed through a different path (see packet captures)

NOTE: all captures are taken on interfaces on SW2 that are connecting to SW1 https://t.co/W6P7aM8AR9

Once i changed it on SW1, the BPDUs that were sent to the STP multicast address each switch is subscribed to, SW2 received BPDU with the flag changed for the port priority for Gi0/1

Gi0/1 = 16, not beats Gi0/0 = 128.1

Now the root port was changed to Gi0/1.

Since we only have two switches, i wanted to see the behavior for the 3rd and 4th tie breakers

For the 3rd tie breaker, i changed the port priority of Gi0/1 on SW1 (The root) to 16

NOTE: port priority numbers can be configured in increments of 16

the election process of the root port is as follows:

1. Lowest cost to root
2. Lowest neighbor BID (bridge ID - Priority and Mac address)
3. lowest neighbor port priority
4. lowest neighbor internal port number

Cost (in a layer 2 topology) references the bandwidth speed of every egress port along the path to the root switch.

Egress meaning "exit" point

Once the root switch is elected in a Layer 2 topology, all non-root switches need to identify the best path to the root switch.

the best path, would be indicated on a non-root switch as the root port == a port with the lowest cost to the root.

In today's CCIE studies, i wanted to do a quick 30 min lab investigating the behavior of Root Port election on a non-root switch that only has redundant connections to the Root switch.

This was fun to break it, a great way to learn! Many design considerations to remember!
As we see, the command "sh span vlan 60" on the MST region shows us a PVST Inc.

As you can see in the screenshots, we see the following:

1. Region Red blocked the port connecting to SW5,
2. In the Wireshark capture a TCN was generated for VLANs 40,50,60 since they are apart of the same MSTP instance (Instance 2) but not for VLANs 10,20,30 (MSTI 1).
If not, it failed a the "PVST simulation check" --> Use to ensure a loop free topo.

So what happened?

The switches in Region Red found that it received a superior BPDU for "only" VLAN 60. Remember, MSTP to PVST communication happens using a VLAN 1 BPDU. So the value has to be consistent for all VLANs

So i wanted to test it.

Region Red is the Root for all VLANs --> (1,10,20,30,40,50,60) with a priority of 4096

I changed the priority for VLAN 60 "only" on SW5 to 0

What does that mean?

There has to be consistency . Either the MSTP is the root for all VLANs and forwards BPDUs for each VLAN, or it doesn't. We can't load balance between MSTP and non-MSTP domains.

Note: "only the VLAN 1 PVST BPDU is used for IST (MSTP) and that the IST BPDU is a one-to-many translation of IST BPDUs to all PVST BPDUs to all PVST BPDUs. " - (Source: Cisco CCNP/CCIE ENCOR OCG pg89)
So MSTP region red is the Root for All VLANs mentioned above.
What the PVST SM does is send PVST+ BPDUs for each VLAN (In this case 7 VLANS (1,10,20,30,40,50,60)
For MSTP switches to communicate with switches running a a flavor of STP that is not MSTP (mentioned above) will have to use the PVST simulation mechanism.
A MSTP region Boundary is any port that connects to a switch that is in a different MSTP region or that connects to a STP domain not running MSTP or in it's region (RPVST, STP 802.1D, PVST)

So in conclusion, the information for instance 1 and instance 2 was nested in a MSTP BPDU from the IST (Instance 0). Those instances that were nested are called M-records.
Since both Region Red and Region Blue were both running MSTP, the PVST mechanism was not used for communication between different domains/regions. the stp protocol used to communicate was MSTP
(As shown in the packet capture and screenshot of the output of the command "show spanning-tree mst detail")
As a note, the IST (MSTI 0) is the ONLY spanning tree instance that sends and recieves BPDUs; all other STP instance information are contained in M-records, which are encapsulated in MSTP BPDUs
the CIST is inside an MST region is the same as the CST outside a region.

An CST (common spanning tree), as a refresher is the single instance of STP used for all VLANs. For example, If there are 500 VLANs, only 1 instance of STP will be running. 1 instance == 1 topology. No PVST
An IST (internal spanning tree), as a refresher is the spanning tree that runs in a MSTP region.
I found that CIST (A common and internal spanning tree) - is a collection of IST in each MSTP region and the CST that interconnects the MSTP regions and single spanning trees.

MSTP Region Red and MSTP Region Carolina Blue was brought online

To make them different regions, i simply made the revision number different for both within MSTP Configuration mode.

MSTP makes the decisions for all vlans by that VLAN 1 BPDU. This is dangerous to say the list, but this is how cisco built it. I will go into detail later this week of how the election process of STP happens for boundary interfaces in a MSTP region facing a PVST domain (switch)

For MSTP and PVST to work, either the PVST domain is the root or the MSTP region is the root for all vlans. It CANNOT be just for 1 or 2 vlans. because MSTP checks all the vlans based on the BPDU from VLAN 1 from the PVST switch.
NOTE: instance 0 contained vlans not specified in any other instances: the default instance: instance 1 contained vlan 10,20,30: instance 2 contained vlan 40,50,60)

the MST region named : The_Speed_Force (DC the Flash fan lol)

SW2 was the root for the MSTP instance 0-1 by setting the priority to 8192

SW3 was the root for instance 2 by doing the same thing

What does this mean? Well instead of doing STP calculations for each VLAN (which would be 200 calculations, big burden on the CPU), for our MST example, there only needs to be calculations for 2 instances

VLANs 2-100 == MST instance 1
VLANs 101-200 == MST instance 2

100 VLANs can be configured for instance 1
the next 100 VLANs can be configured for instance 2
In MST (as it compares to STP), multiple vlans can be mapped to 1 instance. crazy right? Here's what i mean, let's take our 200 vlan example
So what can we do to eliminate this? We have a virtual chassis that will link multiple boxes as one, right? but today wasn't about that. So another way we can do this is utilizing MST.
Again, ALOT of WORK.
Set it's Mac address table aging timer to the forwarding delay timer and wiping it's mac address table for mac address that haven't communicated in that new Mac address table aging timer window.
That's alot of work (CPU power) for the box. What happens if a link that is in a forwarding state goes down? A TCN will be generated, which will cause the entire Layer 2 topology to :
So what happens if we have 200 vlans? Same math; 200 VLANs == 200 STP instances. Meaning that a calculation needs to happen for each VLAN.

In regular STP, 1 VLAN maps to 1 instance of STP. What does that mean?

It means for each VLAN, a calculation needs to happen for that one VLAN. So lets keep it simple for just regular STP: 1 VLAN == 1 STP instance.

So SW1 will continue to "Dispute" it until its fixed because a ALT (blocking) port shouldn't be forwarding frame let alone saying it is the root!

the SW1 (being the root) will "Dispute" with SW2 about why it received a BPDU from SW2 (in the Wireshark capture) saying it is the root, although in SW1 database it known SW2 to be the Non-root switch and to be blocking. So something isn't right
Since SW1 is the configured as the root, and it see it's receiving BPDUs on a link that's supposed to be blocking,
Now what would happen if Gi0/1 on SW2 starts sending BPDUs? Chaos

So SW2 (since it did not win the Root bridge election) should be sending inferior BPDUs to SW1 with on it's Designated port link. And Gi0/1 on SW2 which is in ALT mode (blocking) should not be sending out BPDUs or forwarding frames but it will receive it.
So lets focus on SW2 right now.
SW2 is the non-root switch in this case. So it chose Gi0/0 has it's Designated port since it went through the election process and found Gi0/0 has a lower port priority than Gi0/1.
As you can see, SW1 is the root. and Gi0/0 on SW1 has a port role of Designated (along with Gi0/1 or any other ports on a root)
So in my diagram, i have 2 switches, redundant links, Right? Perf
Let me break it down for you:
If a switch receives a BPDU, it makes sure that the BPDU it did receive match the port role/state of the interface.
STP Dispute does this:
So what is STP Dispute? First things first, this isn't something you configure (or enable) on the switch. It is built into STP.

Cisco gives you the option to save those files either locally or external (Windows server, Linux Server, etc) shown within the screenshots

For me, i renamed my files the current date and switch i am working on to remember in case i need to refer back to it.

For Cisco, the switch configuration and the vlan.dat files are two different critical files.

The vlan.dat file is where the VLAN or VTP configuration are written to.
The switch configuration file is where the configuration of the device sits.

In the result of the following:

1. Accidental deletion of that file
2. Accidental deletion of vlans
3. A VTP switch with a higher revision number has changed the existing vlan configuration for the entire Layer 2 cisco topology including switches.
2. Device has become faulty
Generally in computing, it is important best practice to have backups of critical files.

Tonight's CCIE studies covers the VLAN Database and File Management on Cisco Devices.

This was a fun, quick and dirty lab!

As you can see in the screenshots, after i "pruned" VLAN 30 from SW2 trunk links and its respective neighbor links, no longer was ARP message reaching SW2. So now our CPU does not need to process that traffic.

Since VLAN 30 existed on all Switches and were allowed on all trunks, those ARPs were sent to SW2 even though Network Engineer doesn't plan to currently assign any switchports to VLAN 30. How can we prevent unwanted traffic to and from SW2, we manually "prune" VLAN 30.
ARP request are broadcast messages. Switches will forward broadcast (or unknown unicast frames) out of all ports except the port it received the initial frame on.

With the trunk links between the Layer 2 topology allowing all vlans, if PC9 (IP 10.10.30.150/24) pings an IP address that is on this VLAN 30 that is does not exist in our VLAN physically, the PC will never recieve a response to its ARP request.
SW2 did not have any endpoints within VLAN 30. But for testing this theory, i connected PC9 to SW1 and assigned it to VLAN 30.
(nor does the Network Engineer plan to assign ports on the switch to a specific VLAN). This was the case for SW2

The purpose of "Manual VLAN Pruning" or "VTP Pruning" is to prevent the amount of unnecessary broadcast frame to traverse a trunk link if switches within the topology do not have endpoints in a specific VLAN

In my topology i created, i have a redundant layer 2 network between SW1, SW2 and SW3 (with SW1 being the root due to having the lowest BID).

PC6 and Pc5 are in VLAN 10 (STAFF) and PC4 and PC3 are int VLAN 20 (EXECs). PC9 and PC8 are in VLAN 30 (CONTRACTORs).

Tonight's CCIE Lab consisted of revisiting "Manual VLAN Pruning"

The port LED is set to the color orange and, when you issue the show interfaces command, the port status shows err-disabled." - Source: https://t.co/2Gz28d8zV2

In other words, the port is automatically disabled by the switch operating system software because of an error condition that is encountered on the port.

When a port is error disabled, it is effectively shut down and no traffic is sent or received on that port.
"If the configuration shows a port to be enabled, but software on the switch detects an error situation on the port, the software shuts down that port.

I recreated in my environment utilizing BPDUguard (which shuts down a port if it received a BPDU) in which i enabled it on gi 0/0 on SW2.

Another important reason why i am working on becoming familiar with LLDP, is that it is a open standard. Meaning that most vendors (Fortinet, Swall, Aruba) support this Layer 2 feature. Thank you CS for reminding of this admin skill

Port description TLV
System name TLV
System description TLV
System capabilities TLV
Management Address TLV

I found that LLDP had key values (like the mac address of it's neighbor) in comparison to CDP.

Remembering that LLDP uses TLVs (Type, Length and Value) to receive information about it's neighbor. Here is some examples of some TLV's

1. Domain Name
2. Crypto Keys
3. AAA enabled
4. At least 1 local username set up
5. Enable password to be set
6. Enabling SSH under line vty 0 4

From the Linux PC (All the way on the left) i was able to reach SW2 (in a difference LAN) via LLDP.

Before recreating this lab, i had to also revisit SSH and prerequisites of enabling it on a cisco device.

Tonight's CCIE studies involved revisiting LLDP,CDP and SSH. I found that the importance of this skill is to be able to map out your network without having physical being able to see it.

After todays research on MTU

#HaitianNetworkEngineer
#BlackTechTwitter
#FutureDrAntoine https://t.co/QtctUd3ZuF

As you can see in the packet capture, this caused the packets to be fragmented in the Wireshark capture.

We will continue to investigate this further!

After some research, we found that we can manipulate the packets coming ingress to R2 to advertise to PC1 that the MSS is 1360. Forcing the packets coming into R2 on the interface configured with the "ip tcp adjust-mss 1360"

Which equals 1400 MTU. What happens if the packets we are sending are still sending packets from the source (PC1) are above the MTU of the interface towards R1 when the DF bit is set? We confirmed the packet is dropped.

We manipulated the MTU of the R2's interface towards R1 to 1400 which means the following for packets leaving R2:

1360 Bytes= Payload
20 Bytes = TCP header
20 Bytes = IP Header
With the help of JM , we confirmed by default the MTU of an interface is 1500 bytes. So why not break it?

Today's CCIE studies continued with the investigation of MTU and MSS

The additional headers from the tunneling technologies, reduce the amount of space we have for payload, cause packets to be fragmented more.

I wanted to emulate in a lab as to what happens when the packets leaving a host is set for a MSS higher than the interface's MTU.
So for employees to connect to the main office where files are hosted at their on site server, VPN or another tunneling technology is used to connect to the site, remotely.
Why have i found this important to understand for my Layer 2 studies and understanding? In today's world, most companies have transitioned to a remote workforce.

1460 (PAYLOAD) + 20 (TCP) + 20 (IP) = 1500 bytes + 14 (ETHERNET) = 1514 bytes in total.

Anything above 1500 bytes (if using defaults) would not be transmitted onto the wire.

The breakdown would be this

1460 bytes of payload for TCP.
20 bytes for the TCP header.
20 bytes for the IP header.
14 bytes for the Ethernet header.
Let's say we are using defaults on our devices and the MTU size on each interface is 1500 + 14 for ethernet (L2 header and trailer)

When enabled, UDLD sends its own protocol packets to the multicast address (0100.0ccc.cccc). Knowing how multicast works, if the link does not "recieve" a UDLD packet with its own Device ID and port ID, but is still transmitting UDLD packets, the link is unidirectional.
